<!DOCTYPE recipeml PUBLIC "-//FormatData//DTD RecipeML 0.5//EN" "http://www.formatdata.com/recipeml/recipeml.dtd">
<?xml-stylesheet href="recipe.xml" type="text/xsl"?>
<recipeml xmlns="http://www.formatdata.com/recipeml/recipeml.dtd" xmlns:x="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" version="0.5">
  <meta content="Saturday December 30, 2006" name="DC.Date"/>
  <meta content="Renate" name="DC.Creator"/>
  <recipe id="Pfefferkuchen" system="metric">
    <head>
      <title>Pfefferkuchen</title>
      <categories>
        <cat class="main">Cookies</cat>
        <cat class="sub">Rolled</cat>
        <cat class="region">Germany</cat>
        <cat class="diet">Dairy-free</cat>
      </categories>
    </head>
    <description>Pfefferkuchen are a type of Lebkuchen, Germany's famous spiced
    cookies. Although there are many varieties of Lebkuchen, they all have in
    common nuts, cloves, and resting the dough for a day or, like these, weeks.
    Renate wrote that these are for "foresighted Christmas bakers, who already
    think about Lebkuchen in November." The cookies come out chewy rather than
    crispy, but the baking time is easily converted for use as
    construction materials.</description>
    <ingredients>
      <ing-div>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>250</qty>
            <unit>g</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>honey</item>
<!--3/4 c. honey-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>600</qty>
            <unit>g</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>sugar</item>
<!--3 c. sugar-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <range>
              <q1>4</q1>
              <q2>6</q2>
            </range>
            <unit>Tbs</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>rum</item>
<!--4 to 6 T rum-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>1/2</qty>
              <unit>Tbs</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>baker's ammonia</item>
<!--1/2 T baker's ammonia-->
          </alt-ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>1/2</qty>
              <unit>Tbs</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>baking powder</item>
<!--baking powder-->
          </alt-ing>
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>1</qty>
              <unit>Tbs</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>potash</item>
<!--1 T potash-->
          </alt-ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>1</qty>
              <unit>Tbs</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>baking soda</item>
<!--baking soda-->
          </alt-ing>
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>900</qty>
            <unit>g</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>flour</item>
<!--6 1/4 c. flour-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>65</qty>
              <unit>g</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>citron</item>
            <prep>finely chopped</prep>
<!--1/3 c. citron-->
          </alt-ing>
          <alt-ing>
            <amt>
              <qty>65</qty>
              <unit>g</unit>
            </amt>
            <item>candied ginger</item>
            <prep>finely chopped</prep>
<!--candied ginger, finely chopped-->
          </alt-ing>
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>65</qty>
            <unit>g</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>sliced almonds</item>
          <prep>ground</prep>
<!--1/2 c. sliced almonds, ground-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>1</qty>
            <unit>Tbs</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>cocoa</item>
<!--1 T cocoa-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <range>
              <q1>1/2</q1>
              <q2>1</q2>
            </range>
            <unit>Tbs</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>cloves</item>
<!--1 T cloves-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>1</qty>
            <unit>Tbs</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>cinnamon</item>
<!--1 T cinnamon-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <item>grated zest of one lemon</item>
<!--grated zest of one lemon-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>4</qty>
          </amt>
          <item>eggs</item>
<!--4 eggs-->
        </ing>
      </ing-div>
      <ing-div>
	    <title>Lemon glaze:</title>
<!--Lemon glaze:-->
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>2 1/2</qty>
            <unit>Tbs</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>hot water</item>
<!--2 1/2 T hot water-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>1 1/4</qty>
            <unit>tsp</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>lemon extract</item>
<!--1 1/4 t lemon extract-->
        </ing>
        <ing>
          <amt>
            <qty>150</qty>
            <unit>g</unit>
          </amt>
          <item>powdered sugar.</item>
<!--1 1/4 c powdered sugar.-->
        </ing>
      </ing-div>
    </ingredients>
    <directions>
    <dir-div>
      <note>Do not double this recipe</note>

      <step>Heat the honey, either in a double boiler or while still in the
      jar in a small pot of simmering water (this last method is good if your
      honey has crystalized). Add sugar and stir over heat until dissolved.
      Dissolve baker's ammonia/baking powder and potash/baking soda in 4 T
      rum. Stir together dry ingredients in a large bowl.</step>

      <step>Add honey-sugar mixture, rum-leavening mixture and eggs to dry
      ingredients. Using a stand mixer or your hands, mix together until
      combined. If the dough is dry and crumbly, add up to two more
      tablespoons rum to bring dough together. Once the dough comes together,
      knead quickly on your work surface.</step>

      <step>Place into an airtight container (minimum <size><qty>2</qty>
      <unit>L</unit></size>). If there is a large gap to the top, cover with
      plastic wrap. Store in your refrigerator for two to three weeks.</step>

      <step><x:img src="/images/pfefferkuchen.jpg" class="photo"
      alt="[Plate of pfefferkuchen, (c) 2007 Susan J. Talbutt, all rights
      reserved]" />Preheat oven to <temp><qty>120</qty><tempunit unit="C"
      system="metric">degrees</tempunit><!--250  degrees--></temp> (yes,
      <temp><qty>120</qty><tempunit unit="C"
      system="metric">degrees</tempunit><!--250  degrees--></temp>). Roll dough
      very thin, cut with cutters, and bake on parchment-lined sheets 15 to 17
      minutes. Cool. Whisk together the ingredients for the lemon glaze until
      all lumps are gone. Brush with glaze. Store in an airtight
      container.</step>
    </dir-div>
    <dir-div>
      <title>For gingerbread construction</title>
      <step>Preheat oven to <temp><qty>150</qty><tempunit unit="C"
      system="metric">degrees</tempunit><!--250  degrees--></temp>. Roll dough
      <size><qty>1/2</qty>-<unit>cm</unit></size> thick. Cut pieces out with a
      smallish, finely-serrated knife (<x:strong>not a bread or cake
      knife</x:strong>); work from the corners inward, to keep the dough from
      stretching and distorting the shapes. Bake on parchment-lined sheets 20 to
      30 minutes, longer for larger pieces. Cool. Double check the shape of the
      baked pieces with the patterns. For the most egregiously out of shape
      pieces, trim with a serrated bread or cake knife by slowly scoring the top
      of the piece and then cutting gently with a bit more speed and pressure.
      Assemble with royal icing.</step>
    </dir-div>
    </directions>
  </recipe>
